hands_on_practices.solution:
1. Free energies at optimal gap magnitude Δ for each phase:

For a generic phase with quadratic coefficient α_eff and quartic coefficient β,
$$F_{\min}=-\frac{\alpha_{\rm eff}^2}{4\,\beta}\,. $$

2. Identify α_eff and β for A- and B-phases with anisotropy γ:

– A-phase aligns $\boldsymbol l\parallel z$ so $A_{\mu z}=0$, hence no γ–penalty:
$$\alpha_A=\alpha,\quad \beta_A;\quad
F_A=-\frac{\alpha^2}{4\,\beta_A}\,. $$

– B-phase is isotropic in orbital space so 
$\sum_{\mu,i}|A_{\mu z}|^2=\tfrac13\Tr(A^\dagger A)$,
$$\alpha_B=\alpha+\frac{\gamma}{3},\quad \beta_B;\quad
F_B=-\frac{(\alpha+\gamma/3)^2}{4\,\beta_B}\,. $$

3. Use weak-coupling result $R=E_{c,B}/E_{c,A}=6/5$ at γ=0:

$$\frac{E_{c,B}(0)}{E_{c,A}(0)}
=\frac{\alpha^2/(4\,\beta_B)}{\alpha^2/(4\,\beta_A)}
=\frac{\beta_A}{\beta_B}=\frac{6}{5}
\;\Longrightarrow\;\frac{\beta_B}{\beta_A}=\frac{5}{6}\,. $$

4. Equate $F_A=F_B$ at critical γ:

$$\frac{\alpha^2}{4\,\beta_A}
=\frac{(\alpha+\gamma/3)^2}{4\,\beta_B}
\;\Longrightarrow\;
\alpha^2\beta_B=(\alpha+\gamma/3)^2\beta_A
\;\Longrightarrow\;
\alpha^2\frac{5}{6}=(\alpha+\gamma/3)^2. $$

5. Define $x=\gamma/(-\alpha)>0$ (recall α<0), so
$$\alpha+\frac{\gamma}{3}=-|\alpha|\Bigl(1-\frac{x}{3}\Bigr),$$
and $|\alpha|^2(1-\tfrac{x}{3})^2=\tfrac{5}{6}|\alpha|^2$,
hence
$$(1-\tfrac{x}{3})^2=\frac{5}{6}
\;\Longrightarrow\;
1-\frac{x}{3}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{5}{6}}.$$

6. Choose the minus sign for the smallest positive x:
$$1-\frac{x}{3}=\sqrt{\tfrac{5}{6}}
\;\Longrightarrow\;
\frac{x}{3}=1-\sqrt{\tfrac{5}{6}}
\;\Longrightarrow\;
x=3\Bigl(1-\sqrt{\tfrac{5}{6}}\Bigr)
=3-\frac{\sqrt{30}}{2}\,. $$
